data.content:
In xUnit, setup/teardown is handled via constructors and interfaces — not attributes:

| NUnit | xUnit Equivalent |
|---|---|
| `[SetUp]` | Constructor |
| `[TearDown]` | `IDisposable.Dispose()` |
| `[OneTimeSetUp]` | `IClassFixture<T>` constructor |
| `[OneTimeTearDown]` | `IClassFixture<T>.Dispose()` |

Here's your converted class:

```csharp
public class DatabaseFixture : IDisposable
{
    public DatabaseFixture()
    {
        Database.Initialize();
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Database.Cleanup();
    }
}

public class CustomerRepositoryTests : IClassFixture<DatabaseFixture>, IDisposable
{
    private readonly DbContext _context;
    private readonly CustomerRepository _repo;

    public CustomerRepositoryTests(DatabaseFixture fixture)
    {
        // Per-test setup (replaces [SetUp])
        _context = new TestDbContext();
        _repo = new CustomerRepository(_context);
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        // Per-test teardown (replaces [TearDown])
        _context.Dispose();
    }

    [Fact]
    public void FindById_ExistingCustomer_ReturnsCustomer()
    {
        var customer = _repo.FindById(1);
        Assert.NotNull(customer);
        Assert.Equal("Alice", customer.Name);
    }
}
```

Key points:
- **`IClassFixture<T>`** — xUnit creates `DatabaseFixture` once, shares it across all tests, then disposes it. This replaces `[OneTimeSetUp]`/`[OneTimeTearDown]`.
- **Constructor/`IDisposable`** — xUnit creates a new test class instance per test, so the constructor replaces `[SetUp]` and `Dispose()` replaces `[TearDown]`.
- If you need to share the fixture across multiple test *classes*, use `ICollectionFixture<T>` with a `[Collection]` attribute instead.
